title: For Trade:  Springfield 1911 mico compact .45
postcontent:
The Micro Compact G.I. has a 3" barrel and a framer that's smaller than an Officer's size frame, giving it a weight of just 33 ounces, and making it ideal for carry.

The frame and slide are forged steel, and are parkerized. The 3" bull barrel is fully supported and ramped, and is also parkerized. Parkerizing gives the pistol a finish that's much tougher than anodizing.

The sights on the pistol are original G.I. style, with a low profile notched rear sight and low rounded front sight blade.

The grip safety is flat, just like the old G.I. 1911's, as is the trigger. Trigger pull on the Micro Compact G.I. is five to six pounds, which is a good pull weight for a carry pistol.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1997 Harley Heritage Springer
location: Smithfield, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
When you roll up on this baby, heads are gonna turn, that's just the nature of the beast when you ride a rarely seen classic Harley. All the Harley guys take notice, alot come over to check it out, admire the show room condition and compliment it, it's looks, it's sound, it's nostalgia !
There won't be another like it in the parking lot, no, most of them look like my other Harley, it's black with alot of chrome. Just like everyone else's. Not this one ....... 

1997 Harley Davidson Heritage Springer FLSTS

I have 2 Harleys and I'm looking to trade the museum piece Harley for a boat !!! Would even consider a convertible sports car for my wife since that's on the list also. I

Museum quality !!!

The sound....oh, the sound.......that Evolution V-twin ( EVO ) is normally aspirated and the sound all Harley owners want, but they can't get it with the modern fuel injected engines, tho' they try.

Do notice the original fishtail pipes !!!

Truly a collectors dream !!! This bike is a time capsule !!! You would search a very long time to find another 1997 OLD BOY with such low original miles!

Since this bike is completely original, you could call it a blank canvas. All Harley riders/owners add options and accessories to "make it their own", to allow their personality to show in their bike. This bike has been left near stock, even the tires are original and are mint. Not a crack anywhere! Only added Harley OEM options are the backrests. And they cost me a fortune a few months ago!!! OOooopppps, also added the light visors up front, EVERY classic needs them !

This bike sits as it did when it came off the showroom floor, sans the above aforementioned !!!

2,821 miles. That is NOT a misprint.

This bike should be shown and win every show it's entered in. How often do you see an all original 17 year old bike with 2,821 miles?

Unmolested, untouched as it came off the showroom floor. 

Fresh full synthetic oil.
New Harley battery.

This bike was owned by a 74 year old gentleman that didn't ride it, obviously.

This bike had been on my bucket list a LONG time and I'm not desperate to trade it, I will keep it if I don't get enough cash or a trade of equal value. I've had it awhile and it's time to let it go, I'm positioning for a move and can't take everything with me.

This "Old Boy" is an attention magnet !!! 

I'll continue to ride it a little until it's gone.

Everybody loves it, it's so classic and stylish. 

The history of the 1997 Heritage Springer is that it was designed after the 1948 Panhead. Those in the bike world refer to this as the "Old Boy", after the '48 Panhead.


Please don't waste my time or yours with idiotic offers, price is FIRM !!!  It's a 17 year old brand new bike. Go find another with 2,821 miles and in this condition. One thing is for sure, the value of this bike will only go up, never down. If you buy a brand new 2014 Harley today, 5 years from now it's worth $12,000.00?
What will this be worth in 5 years, over $20,000.00 for sure. 
There is a guy in New Jersey with a twin to this bike, his only has 1,000 miles, but he's asking OVER $30,000.00 !!! Ridiculous !

NO RIDES WITHOUT ALL THE CASH IN MY HAND !

Will also trade for Leer jet. Will need flying lessons.

If what you are offering on trade isn't worth $19,500.00 to you, it isn't worth it to me either. You know what you have, you know what it's worth, and I'm not stupid or easy to pull one over on, so let's keep it straight, please.

ALSO..............the truck in the barn is NOT mine, just a place to shoot a pic. It's NOT for sale.

THANKS !!!!!!!

DEALERS NOT WELCOME !!!    WILL NOT SHIP ANYWHERE <>< NOT EVEN IN THE STATES <>< !!!

title: For Sale:  CZ-97 in .45acp - Rush sale $600
location: Leesburg, Sterling, Chantilly, Northern Virginia, Virginia
postcontent:
Please read everything!

Anyone that knows me knows that I'm a bit of a CZ nut. Any anyone that's shot with my has probably seen this CZ-97, which has been one of my most well used and loved CZs. That said, there is a once in a blue moon opportunity to pick up a gun my collection needs, and I don't have the cash for it. While this gun has been great, it is replacable. So, reluctantly, I have to turn it into cash quickly to get this collectible before the auction expires. 

I HAVE to sell this - no trades, though I typically love trades. I'm pricing for sale because I need to move it in the next two days. If I don't have enough cash by Tuesday, my fairy princess slips out of my hands forever. And I have to get $600. I am happy to ship on your dime, which ought to be only about $30. I'm only selling to raise enough cash for the auction, and if I lose on Tuesday, then I'm going to hold on to it. Need a firm buyer by Tuesday, but I don't have to meet by then - I will need to meet or get cash by Friday though, which is when I'll expect to have to send payment. Please plan accordingly when messaging me. I'm in Leesburg, but work in Sterling. 

The gun has the factory wood grips on it, and has two Mec-gar 10 round mags that go with it. Unlike most CZs, this one likes lead bullets, as you can see, it eats a regular diet of my SWC match loads. Fair warning - the slide stop catches on some .45 rounds that are close to max .45 COAL. If you shoot factory ammo, shop around to find one that it likes. If you reload, load short. 

EDIT: Probably ought to talk about the gun a little. The CZ-97 is a .45acp - slide moves inside the frame, like other CZ's. There is a removable screw in barrel bushing, similar to a 1911. The mag is a double stack, 10 round mag, though I believe there are after market mags. The two that come with it have finger rests, though the gun itself is pretty large - comparable to most double stack .45's, plus maybe even a little, because the grips are rounded. The finish is parked, though I've kept it well oiled. There is no aftermarket hardware on it - its like you would get one from the factory. This is also a B, not a BD - no decocker on this model. It was manufactured in 2003.
